Visualizations in R

Sarah Wellberg

Most of the examples use a set of 100 pre- and post-test scores on a 50-item test.

Some examples are also from the data frame data, printed below.

id score grade color teacher
s100 85 10 red Mr.Stangl
s200 95 10 orange Ms.Wellberg
s300 90 9 yellow Ms.Wellberg
s400 80 9 green Mr.Stangl
s500 70 10 blue Mr.Stangl
s600 75 9 purple Ms.Wellberg


Basic Graphs


The following are the basic codes for the main types of graphics. Note that the default settings are very basic. R will use the the specified variable names for the axes labels and the main title, and the axes will be scaled based on the minimum and maximum data values.


Histograms


Basic Code: hist(vector).

Example:

Well make the most basic histogram of pre-test scores.

hist(scores$pre)



Setting Bin Width

You can set the x-values for which histogram bins begin and end by using the breaks option. Id recommend using the seq function to create the vector of evenly-spaced values.

Code:

hist(vector, 
     breaks = seq(start, end, increment)

Example:

Lets make a histogram of the pre-test scores with bins of width 2.5 using the seq command

The minimum score is 12, and the maximum is 29. Ill make the bins go from 10 to 30.

hist(scores$pre,
     breaks = seq(10, 30, 2.5))

Scatter Plots


Basic Code: plot(x_vector, y_vector).

Example:

Lets plot pre-test scores on the x-axis and post-test scores on the y-axis.

plot(scores$pre,
     scores$post)



Shapes

You can change the shape of the data points that get plotted using the pch option. The options are presented in the image below.

The options 0-25 can be written as numbers, the rest (and any other symbol you want to use) need to be in quotation marks.

Code:

plot(x,
     y,
     pch = value)

Number Example:

Lets make the pre- and post-test scores plot with filled-in, right-side-up triangles using option 17.

plot(scores$pre,
     scores$post,
     pch = 17)


Character Example:

Lets make the data points show up as s.

plot(scores$pre,
     scores$post,
     pch = "s")



Multiple sets of points on one plot

Once you have used the plot function to make a scatter plot, you can add another set of points to the plot by using the points function.

Notes:

  • The plot will keep the scale limits from the plot function, so the new poitns may get cut off if the window isnt big enough.

  • The new points will have the default shape and color. Youll want to change the color or shape settings and add a legend, so you can tell which points represent which data sets. (See the General Options and Legend sections for details)

Basic Code:

plot(x1, y1)
points(x2, y2)

Example:

We have a second set of pre- and post-test scores. Lets plot these two sets of scores on the same axes.

Ill also set the axes limits to be the min and max values for the two data sets.

# Min/Max
  xmin <- min(scores$pre, scores2$pre)
  xmax <- max(scores$pre, scores2$pre)

  ymin <- min(scores$post, scores2$post)
  ymax <- max(scores$post, scores2$post)

# Plots
  plot(scores$pre,
       scores$post,
       xlim = c(xmin, xmax),
       ylim = c(ymin, ymax),
       xlab = "Pre-Test Scores",
       ylab = "Post-Test Scores")
  points(scores2$pre,
         scores2$post,
         col = "blue")
  legend("topleft",
         legend = c("data1", "data2"),
         text.col = c("black", "blue"),
         bty = "n")

Bar Graphs


You can either graph a vector of values or a whole matrix of values.


Graphing one vector

Basic Code: barplot(vector)

Example:

Lets make a bargraph of the pre-test scores for the first 5 students in the data frame.

barplot(scores$pre[1:5])

Note that the bars are unlabeled. To give them labels, use the option names.arg = vector

Code: barplot(vector, names.arg = names_vector)

Example:

Well add labels to the bars in the graph above.

barplot(scores$pre[1:5],
        names.arg = paste("Student", 1:5))



Graphing multiple values

If you want multiple values ploted, you need to make a matrix of values with the data that will be grouped together in columns.

Youll want to add a legend, so that people can tell which values are which. See the legends tab for details.

Note that you cant change the names once youve made a matrix. If you want to add column and row names to keep track of your data (which you should), make a data frame first, chagne the names, then turn it into a matrix.

Matrix Example:

Lets plot both the pre- and post-test scores for the first 5 students. Well need to make a matrix where each column represents a student, the pre-test scores are in the first row, and the post-test scores are in the second row.

score_matrix <- data.frame(rbind(scores$pre[1:5],
                                 scores$post[1:5]))
                                 
names(score_matrix) <- paste("s", 1:5, sep = "")
row.names(score_matrix) <- c("pre", "post")

score_matrix %<>% as.matrix()
s1 s2 s3 s4 s5
pre 19 24 23 20 15
post 30 41 33 33 26



  1. Stacked bars

The default setting is for the bars to be stacked. The first row values will be on the bottom, and the last row will be on the top.

Code: barplot(matrix)

Example:

barplot(score_matrix,
        names.arg = paste("Student", 1:5))


  1. Side-by-side bars

If you want the bars to be next to each other, use the beside = TRUE option. The first row will be on the left, and the last row will be on the right for each group.

Code: barplot(matrix, beside = TRUE)

Example:

barplot(score_matrix,
        beside = TRUE,
        names.arg = paste("Student", 1:5))

Box Plots


Basic Code: boxplot(vector1, vector2, ...)

Example:

boxplot(scores$pre,
        scores$post)



Naming the Boxes

If you just enter the vectors you want to plot, R will just name them 1, 2, 3,

To use more meaningful labels, use the names option.

You can also add lables to the overall axes. See the Axes section in the General Options tab for details.

Code:

boxplot(vector1, 
        vector2, 
        ...,
        names = c("name1", "name2", ...))

Example:

boxplot(scores$pre,
        scores$post,
        names = c("Pre-Test", "Post-Test"))



Grouping the Data

You can make a st of boxplots for values grouped by a second variable. Itll group the data in alphabetical/numeric order by the grouping variable and automatically name each box with the grouping values.

Code:

boxplot(data_vector ~ grouping_vector)

Example:

Lets make boxplots for the scores in the data data frame grouped by teacher.

boxplot(data$score ~ data$teacher)

General Options


These options can be used with any type of graph.


Axes


There are lots of fancy things you can do with axis labels, but well just do the basics here.


Values

Chose the range of values for each axis by using the xlim and ylim options.

Code:

plot_type(data_vectors,
          xlim = c(xmin, xmax),
          ylim = c(ymin, ymax))

Example:

Lets plot the grade and score values from the data data frame.

plot(data$grade,
     data$score,
     xlim = c(8.5, 10.5),
     ylim = c(60, 100))



Labels

Label your x and y axes variable using the xlab and ylab options.

Code:

plot_type(data_vectors,
          xlab = "X Label",
          ylab = "Y Label")

Example:

plot(data$grade,
     data$score,
     xlab = "Grade",
     ylab = "Score")

Title


You can give your graph a title using the main option.

Note: If you have multiple graphs in a window and want to have a main title for all of them, see the Window Options: Outer Text section.

Code:

plot_type(data_vectors,
          main = "Title")

Example:

plot(data$grade,
     data$score,
     main = "Scores by Grade")

Size


The various cex options let you change the size of different parts of the graph. The number you enter will scale the size. 1 is the default. 2 would double the normal size, and 0.5 would cut the size in half.


Plotted Points

Use cex to change the size of plotted data points.

Code:

plot(x, 
     y, 
     cex = scale)
plot(scores$pre,
     scores$post,
     main = "cex = 2",
     cex = 2)



Axes

Use cex.axis to change the size of the number labels on the axes.

Code:

plot(x, 
     y, 
     cex.axis = scale)

Example

plot(scores$pre,
     scores$post,
     main = "cex.axis = 2",
     cex.axis = 2)



Lables

Use cex.lab to change the size of the variable labels on the axes.

Code:

plot(x, 
     y, 
     cex.lab = scale)

Example

plot(scores$pre,
     scores$post,
     main = "cex.lab = 2",
     cex.lab = 2)



Title

Use cex.main to change the size of the title.

Code:

plot(x, 
     y, 
     cex.main = scale)

Example

plot(scores$pre,
     scores$post,
     main = "cex.main = 2",
     cex.main = 2)

Color


The basic plots are white with black outlines or shades of gray, which is pretty boring.

R has a bunch of colors that you can use. Here is a website with a list of all of the default R colors. Note that there is a weird title page, and you need to scroll down to see the color options.

You can also use hex codes using the format "#code" to get a custom color. Here is a good website for finding hex codes.

Basic Code:

plot_type(data_vectors,
          col = "color_name")



All one color

Lets plot the pre and post-test scores. Well use a hex code to make them hot pink and fill them in, so we can see the color better.

Example:

plot(scores$pre,
     scores$post,
     pch = 16,
     col = "#ff48c0")



Color patterns

You can enter a vector of color names and R will cycle through them as it makes each part of the graph.

Example:

Lets redo the side-by-side score bar graph so that the pre-test scores are blue and the post-test scores are green

barplot(score_matrix,
        beside = TRUE,
        names.arg = paste("Student", 1:5),
        col = c("dodgerblue3", "olivedrab"))



A vector of colors assigned to each data point

If you have a color associated with a specific data point, you can simply call that vector, and each point will be the right color.

If youre going to rearrange your data, make sure the color vector is a variable in the same data frame, so the colors also get rearranged.

Example:

Lets plot the grade and score values from the data data set and color each students point the color listed in their row of the data set. Again, Ill fill them in and make them bigger, so we can see it better.

plot(data$grade,
     data$score,
     pch = 16,
     cex = 1.25,
     col = data$color)



Histogram Borders

The col option changes the fill of histogram bars, and the border option changes the color of the lines outlining the bars.

Code: hist(vector, border = "color")

Example:

Lets make a histogram of the pre-test scores where the bars are gold and the border lines are dark orange

hist(scores$pre,
     breaks = seq(10, 30, 2.5),
     main = "",
     col = "gold",
     border = "darkorange")



Color Continuums

R has some color pallets that you can use to make nice continuums. Just specify have many colors you need, and itll stretch the colors across the spectrum.

  1. Rainbow

Code:

plot_type(data,
          col = rainbow(n))

Example:

barplot(scores$pre[1:25],
        col = rainbow(25))


  1. Heat Colors

Code:

plot_type(data,
          col = heat.colors(n))

Example:

barplot(scores$pre[1:25],
        col = heat.colors(25))


  1. Terrain Colors

Code:

plot_type(data,
          col = terrain.colors(n))

Example:

barplot(scores$pre[1:25],
        col = terrain.colors(25))


  1. Topographical Colors

Code:

plot_type(data,
          col = topo.colors(n))

Example:

barplot(scores$pre[1:25],
        col = topo.colors(25))


  1. Cyan-Magenta Colors

Code:

plot_type(data,
          col = cm.colors(n))

Example:

barplot(scores$pre[1:25],
        col = cm.colors(25))

Lines


You can add different kinds of lines to your graphs. All of these line types require a pre-existing plot and cannot be plotted on their own.

You can create an empty plot by specifying the x and y limits and ploting a single point in the range using the option type = "n"

Code:

plot(x,
     y,
     xlim = c(xmin, xmax),
     ylim = c(ymin, ymax),
     type = "n")

Once you have a plot, you can add as many lines as you want.


Straight Lines


Use the abline function to draw straight lines.


y = mx + b

You can plot a straight line by specifying an intercept and a slope value.

Code: abline(intercept, slope)

Example:

Lets draw the identity line y = x on our scatter plot or pre- and post-test scores to see the shift in scores between the two occasions. The intercept is 0, and the slope is 1.

# Create a plot window first
  plot(scores$pre,
       scores$post,
       xlim = c(10, 35),
       ylim = c(20, 50),
       xlab = "Pre-Test",
       ylab = "Post-Test")

# Plot the line on top
  abline(0, 1)



Vertical Lines

Code: abline(v = xval)

Example:

Lets make a vertical line at x = 25 on our scores scatterplot to see which students earned at least a 50% on the pre-test.

# Create a plot window first
  plot(scores$pre,
       scores$post,
       xlim = c(10, 35),
       ylim = c(20, 50),
       xlab = "Pre-Test",
       ylab = "Post-Test")

# Plot the line on top
  abline(v = 25)



Horizontal Lines

Code: abline(h = yval)

Example:

Lets make a horizontal line at y = 25 on our scores scatterplot to see which students earned at least a 50% on the post-test.

# Create a plot window first
  plot(scores$pre,
       scores$post,
       xlim = c(10, 35),
       ylim = c(20, 50),
       xlab = "Pre-Test",
       ylab = "Post-Test")

# Plot the line on top
  abline(h = 25)

Regression Lines


See the Analysis in R file for more details on regressions.


You can plot a regression line by either calling an existing regression object or by putting the regression model directly into the argument.


Model in the argument

Code: abline(lm(y ~ x))

Example:

Lets add a regression line to our scores scatter plot.

# Create a plot window first
  plot(scores$pre,
       scores$post,
       xlim = c(10, 35),
       ylim = c(20, 50),
       xlab = "Pre-Test",
       ylab = "Post-Test")

# Plot the line on top
  abline(lm(scores$post ~ scores$pre))



Regression Object

Code: abline(reg_object)

Example:

# create a regression object
  score_reg <- lm(scores$post ~ scores$pre)

# Create a plot window first
  plot(scores$pre,
       scores$post,
       xlim = c(10, 35),
       ylim = c(20, 50),
       xlab = "Pre-Test",
       ylab = "Post-Test")

# Plot the line on top
  abline(score_reg)

Lines Connecting Points


If youre using either the plot or points functions, you can connect the data points with a line using the type option.

Code:

plot(x,
     y,
     type = "option")

OR

points(x,
       y,
       type = "option")

The image below shows the different line options.

Default: type = "p"


Warning: The points will connect in the order in which they are plotted, so youll want to arrange the x values in the order you want first.


Example:

Well plot a set of students scores and the time (in hours) they took to complete the test with and without sorting first. The time data set is printed below

score time
25 1.677
29 1.426
29 1.739
31 1.695
27 1.393
25 1.271
27 1.567
20 1.112
30 1.707
25 1.617 
# Plotting the data as-is
  plot(time$time,
       time$score,
       xlab = "Time",
       ylab = "Score",
       type = "o",
       main = "As-Is")

# Arrange by pre-test score  
  time %<>% arrange(time)
  
# Plot the arranged data
  plot(time$time,
       time$score,
       xlab = "Time",
       ylab = "Score",
       type = "o",
       main = "Arranged")

Density Lines


You can graph a density line for a given vector using the following code:

Code: lines(density(vector))



Adding a density line on top of a histogram.

Example:

Lets make a histogram of the pre-test scores with a density line on top.

hist(scores$pre,
     freq = FALSE,
     col = "darkcyan",
     xlab = "Score",
     xlim = c(0, 50),
     breaks = seq(0, 50, 5),
     ylim = c(0, 0.12),
     main = "Pre-Test Score Distribution")
lines(density(scores$pre),
      lwd = 2)



Graphing just the density line(s)

You cant just plot a line. You need an existing plot to put the line on. You can get just the line the show by plotting a histogram where the bars and lines are white.

Example:

Lets graph the density lines for the pre- and post tests on the same set of axes.

hist(scores$pre,
     freq = FALSE,
     col = "white",
     border = "white",
     xlab = "Score",
     xlim = c(0, 50),
     ylim = c(0, 0.12),
     main = "Score Densities")
lines(density(scores$pre),
      lwd = 2)
lines(density(scores$post),
      col = "blue",
      lwd = 2)
legend("topleft",
       legend = c("Pre-Test", "Post-Test"),
       lwd = 2,
       col = c("black", "blue"),
       bty = "n")

Line Options


You can make your lines different colors, widths, and patterns.


Color

Use the same col argument you used for changing the color of the data points.

Code: abline(data, col = "color_name")

Example:

Lets make our scores regression line purple.

# Create a plot window first
  plot(scores$pre,
       scores$post,
       xlim = c(10, 35),
       ylim = c(20, 50),
       xlab = "Pre-Test",
       ylab = "Post-Test")

# Plot the line on top
  abline(lm(scores$post ~ scores$pre),
         col = "purple")



Width

Use the lwd option to change the width of a line. The number you enter will scale the normal line width.

Code: abline(data, lwd = number)

Example:

Lets triple the width of our regression line.

# Create a plot window first
  plot(scores$pre,
       scores$post,
       xlim = c(10, 35),
       ylim = c(20, 50),
       xlab = "Pre-Test",
       ylab = "Post-Test")

# Plot the line on top
  abline(lm(scores$post ~ scores$pre),
         lwd = 3)



Pattern

You can use the lty option to change the line pattern. The options are shown in the image below.


Default: lty = 1

Example:

Lets make our regression line dashed.

# Create a plot window first
  plot(scores$pre,
       scores$post,
       xlim = c(10, 35),
       ylim = c(20, 50),
       xlab = "Pre-Test",
       ylab = "Post-Test")

# Plot the line on top
  abline(lm(scores$post ~ scores$pre),
         lty = 2)

Legends


Lengeds are really helpful if you want to have multiple sets of data in the same plot and need to distinguish between them using different colors and shapes.

Legends are also good for adding correlations to scatter plots, adding SDs to histograms, etc.

You cant make a legend without an existing plot. Use the same type = "n" trick shown in the Lines section to create a blank plot if you just want the legend.


Basics


To create a legend, you need to specify the location & the text (which can be a vector). You can either specify explicit x & y coordinates or use one of the location keywords. I like to just use the keywords for general legends and inset them a bit. The x & y coordinate option is good for labeling individual points on a scatterplot.



Location Keyword

The location keyword options are presented below.

Code: legend("location", legend = "Text")

Example:

Lets plot a histogram of the pre-test scores and use a legend to add the mean and the SD of the scores.

Ill use the paste command to combine the text SD = with the rounded SD for the scores and Mean = with the rounded mean. If you dont round the number, it will print a lot of digits.

hist(scores$pre,
     xlab = "Scores",
     col = "darkorchid",
     main = "Pre-Test Scores")
legend("topleft", 
       legend = c(paste("Mean =", round(mean(scores$pre), 2)),
                  paste("SD =", round(sd(scores$pre), 2))))



Coordinates

You can specify a set of x and y coordinates, and the upper left corner of the legend box will be placed on that point.

Code: legend(x, y, legend = "Text")

Example:

Lets take the test scores scatter plot and label the point for the student who scored the highest on the pre-test.

# Create a plot window first
  plot(scores$pre,
       scores$post,
       xlim = c(10, 35),
       ylim = c(20, 50),
       xlab = "Pre-Test",
       ylab = "Post-Test")

  
# Add Legend
  legend(max(scores$pre),
         scores$post[which(scores$pre == max(scores$pre))],
         legend = "High Score")

Lines & Symbols


You may have noticed in the Basics tab that the text is shifted to the side in the legend boxes. This is because R is making space for a symbol that we havent specified. You can use the same data point symbols and line options that are presented in the Scatterplot and Line sections.


Lines

The same col, lty, and lwd options discussed in the Lines section still apply here. Make sure that you list the legend text extries and the line options in the same order.

Code:

legend("location",
       legend = "Text",
       lwd = width_scale,
       lty = line_option,
       col = "color_name")

Example:

Lets plot our scores along with a regression line and the identity line, for comparison.

# Create a plot window first
  plot(scores$pre,
       scores$post,
       xlim = c(10, 35),
       ylim = c(20, 50),
       xlab = "Pre-Test",
       ylab = "Post-Test")

# Plot the regression line
  abline(lm(scores$post ~ scores$pre),
         lwd = 2,
         col = "red")
  
# Plot the identity line
  abline(0,
         1,
         lwd = 2,
         lty = 2)
  
# Add Legend
  legend("topleft",
         legend = c("Regression", "y = x"),
         lwd = 2,
         lty = c(1, 2),
         col = c("red", "black"))



Symbols

The same pch options apply to the legend.

Code:

legend("location",
       legend = "Text",
       pch = option,
       col = "color_name")

Example:

Lets plot the grade and score values from the data data set and use a legend to specify which data point belongs to which student.

# Plot Data
  plot(data$grade,
       data$score,
       xlim = c(8, 10),
       pch = 15,
       cex = 1.25,
       col = data$color)

# Legend
  legend("topleft",
         legend = data$id,
         pch = 15,
         col = data$color)

Text Color


The col option only changes the color of the line or symbol next to your text.

Use the text.col option to change the color of your text.

If you want both the symbol/line and the text to be the same color, youll need to enter both options.

Code:

legend("location",
       legend = "Text",
       text.col = "color")

Example:

Lets take out the symbols from the grades and scores plot and make the student IDs the corresponding colors instead.

# Plot Data
  plot(data$grade,
       data$score,
       xlim = c(8, 10),
       pch = 15,
       cex = 1.25,
       col = data$color)

# Legend
  legend("topleft",
         legend = data$id,
         text.col = data$color,
         bty = "n")

Border


The bty option is used to change borders (See the Window Options section for more details).

The only border options allowed for legends are the default full border bty = "o" and no border bty = "n". If you want the border, theres no need to write any code. If you dont want a border, use the n option.

Code:

legend(legend = "text",
       bty = "n")

Example:

Lets add the correlation between the pre- and post-test scores as a legend with no border

plot(scores$pre,
     scores$post,
     xlab = "Pre-Test Scores",
     ylab = "Post-Test Scores")
legend("topleft",
       legend = paste("r =", round(cor(scores$pre, scores$post), 2)),
       bty = "n")

Size


Just like with the plots, use the cex options to change the size of elements of your legend.


Symbols and Text

The cex option will change the size of both the symbols and the text in your legend.

Code:

legend("location",
       legend = "Text",
       cex = scale)

Example:

Lets double the size of the legend elements for the grades and scores scatter plot legend.

# Plot Data
  plot(data$grade,
       data$score,
       xlim = c(8, 10),
       pch = 15,
       cex = 1.25,
       col = data$color)

# Legend
  legend("topleft",
         legend = data$id,
         col = data$color,
         pch = 15,
         cex = 2,
         bty = "n")

Only Symbols

Use the pt.cex option to change only the size of the legend symbols.

Code:

legend("location",
       legend = "Text",
       pt.cex = scale)

Example:

Lets double the size of only the symbols for the grades and scores scatter plot legend.

# Plot Data
  plot(data$grade,
       data$score,
       xlim = c(8, 10),
       pch = 15,
       cex = 1.25,
       col = data$color)

# Legend
  legend("topleft",
         legend = data$id,
         col = data$color,
         pch = 15,
         pt.cex = 2,
         bty = "n")



Only Text

There is no command to only change the size of text and not the symbol. If you want to do that, you need to use both the cex option with your desired text size scaling and the pt.cex option set to the default value of 1.

Code:

legend("location",
       legend = "Text",
       cex = text_scale,
       pt.cex = 1)

Example:

Lets double the only size of the text for the grades and scores scatter plot legend.

# Plot Data
  plot(data$grade,
       data$score,
       xlim = c(8, 10),
       pch = 15,
       cex = 1.25,
       col = data$color)

# Legend
  legend("topleft",
         legend = data$id,
         col = data$color,
         pch = 15,
         cex = 2,
         pt.cex = 1,
         bty = "n")

Inset


If you dont want a line or symbol, it can look kind of weird to have the extra space. You can use the inset option to move the legend right/left and up/down.

Code:

legend("location",
       legend = "Text",
       inset = c(horizontal_shift, vertical_shift))

Example:

Lets move the Mean & SD legend for our pre-test scores historgram to the left and up.

hist(scores$pre,
     xlab = "Scores",
     col = "darkorchid",
     main = "Pre-Test Scores")
legend("topleft", 
       legend = c(paste("Mean =", round(mean(scores$pre), 2)),
                  paste("SD =", round(sd(scores$pre), 2))),
       bty = "n",
       inset = c(-0.03, 0.03))

Columns


If you have a lot of entries in your legend, you may want to make multiple columns using the ncol option.

Note that the legend entries will fill in column by column.

Code:

legend("location",
       legend = "Text",
       ncol = number)

Example:

Lets make the grades and scores legend two columns.

# Plot Data
  plot(data$grade,
       data$score,
       xlim = c(8, 10),
       pch = 15,
       cex = 1.25,
       col = data$color)

# Legend
  legend("topleft",
         legend = data$id,
         col = data$color,
         pch = 15,
         ncol = 2,
         bty = "n")

Horizontal Legends


If you want to have the legend print as rows instead of columns, use the horiz option.

Code:

legend("location",
       legend = "Text",
       horiz = TRUE)

Example:

Lets make the grades and scores legend horizontal.

# Plot Data
  plot(data$grade,
       data$score,
       xlim = c(8, 10),
       pch = 15,
       cex = 1.25,
       col = data$color)

# Legend
  legend("topleft",
         legend = data$id,
         col = data$color,
         pch = 15,
         horiz = TRUE)

Window Options


The following options apply to all types of visuals.

You can check the default values for any of these options by typing par() insto the console.


Splitting the Window


You can plot multiple graphs in the same plot window. Note that once you change the way the window is partitioned, it will stay that way until you reset it to the default.

Code: par(mfrow = c(rows, columns))

Default: mfrow = c(1, 1)

Example:

Lets make side-by-side histograms for the pre- and post-test scores

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))

hist(scores$pre,
     freq = FALSE,
     col = "darkcyan",
     xlab = "Score",
     xlim = c(0, 50),
     breaks = seq(min(scores$pre) - (min(scores$pre) %% 5),
                  max(scores$pre) + (5 - (max(scores$pre) %% 5)),
                  5),
     ylim = c(0, 0.1),
     main = "Pre-Test Scores")

hist(scores$post,
     freq = FALSE,
     col = "darkcyan",
     xlab = "Score",
     xlim = c(0, 50),
     breaks = seq(min(scores$post) - (min(scores$post) %% 5),
                  max(scores$post) + (5 - (max(scores$post) %% 5)),
                  5),
     ylim = c(0, 0.1),
     main = "Post-Test Scores")



Resetting the Window

When you have a split window, the next thing you plot will go into the next open space. If you want to start over with a fresh plot instead of adding to whats already there, you can change the mfrow option in the par command.

Example:

Lets say Ive plotted five historgrams in a windown thats split into two rows and three columns, as seen below.

When I plot the next graphs, theyll go into the remaining space and spill over to a new window. Lets say I want to make scatter plots of the pre- and post-test scores where Ive split the data into five groups. If I dont reset the window, itll look like this:

Ill reset the window by reusing the mfrow command, even though Im not changing the number of rows or columns.

par(mfrow = c(2, 3))
for (i in 1:5) {
  hist(samples[,i],
       xlab = "Values",
       main = paste("Histogram", i),
       col = "darkorchid")
}

par(mfrow = c(2, 3)) # Reset window

for (i in 1:5) {
plot(scores$pre[(i + 20*(i - 1)):(i + 20*(i - 1) + 19)], 
     scores$post[(i + 20*(i - 1)):(i + 20*(i - 1) + 19)],
     xlab = "Pre-Test",
     ylab = "Post-Test",
     main = paste("Scatter Plot", i),
     pch = 16,
     col = "olivedrab")
}

Layering Graphs


Most things that get layered already have functions (abline, points, etc), but if you want to layer another graph on top of an existing graph, you can use the new option in the par command.

Note: Itll stack the graphs as they would have been plotted on their own, so youll need to make sure that the axes have the same scale and the title and lables dont interfere with each other.

Code: par(new = TRUE)

Example:

We have a function that plots an item characteristic curve given its item parameter estimates (see the Analysis in R file to get the code for this function). Since it produces a new graph instead of plotting on top of an existing graph like abline does, we need to use the new option if we want to plot multiple ICCs on the same window.

icc(b = -0.4, 
    a = 1.6, 
    color = "darkorchid", 
    title = "ICC Comparison")

par(new = TRUE) # Need this to stack
icc(b = 0.7, 
    a = 0.8, 
    color = "darkcyan",
    title = "") # Leaving this blank.  Could also just rewrite the same title

Outer text


If you have a split graphing window and want to add an overall title, change the outer top margin and add a main text.


Outer top margin

Code: par(oma = c(bottom, left, top, right))

Default: par(oma = c(0, 0, 0, 0))


Outer main text

Code: mtext("text", outer = TRUE)


Example

Lets graph the score histograms, but well add a main title.

par(mfrow = c(1, 2),
    oma = c(0, 0, 2, 0))

hist(scores$pre,
     freq = FALSE,
     col = "darkcyan",
     xlab = "Score",
     xlim = c(0, 50),
     breaks = seq(min(scores$pre) - (min(scores$pre) %% 5),
                  max(scores$pre) + (5 - (max(scores$pre) %% 5)),
                  5),     
     ylim = c(0, 0.1),
     main = "Pre-Test")

hist(scores$post,
     freq = FALSE,
     col = "darkcyan",
     xlab = "Score",
     xlim = c(0, 50),
     breaks = seq(min(scores$post) - (min(scores$post) %% 5),
                  max(scores$post) + (5 - (max(scores$post) %% 5)),
                  5),
     ylim = c(0, 0.1),
     main = "Post-Test")

mtext("Score Distributions",
      outer = TRUE,
      cex = 1.3)

Border Options


You can change the outer border of the main graph by using the bty option

The image below illustrates the different types of outlines you can have.

Code: par(bty = "option")

Example:

Lets plot students pre- and post-test scores. Well make the plot only have borders on the bottom and left sides.

par(bty = "l")
plot(scores$pre,
     scores$post,
     xlab = "Pre-Test Scores",
     ylab = "Post-Test Scores")

Image Sizing


The plot will take the size and shape of the Plots pane in RStudio. If you want to plot multiple graphs in one window, you may want to stretch the Plots pane, so theres more space in whichevery direction you need it.

You can also make the image a certain number of pixels when you use the Export button. You can click Update Preview to see what it will look like with those dimensions before you save.
